<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-435-638  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 435 638.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  June 22 1989 v15 n13 p26(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Virtual people assist in automation; Enterprise Automation as astrategy for automating computer centres. (includes relatedarticle on an Enterprise Automation implementation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Larsen, Bjorn.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Enterprise Automation (EA) is a full strategic approach to theautomation of data processing departments and differs fromAutomated Operations (AO) in an important way.andP;  AO only automatesadvanced console operations and addresses only the visible portionof this process.andP;  EA, by using an automation platform residingoutside of the host complex, integrates nd manages all controlinformation.andP;  Data pouring from the host computer is managed byone or more Control Point machines, which summarize the status ofthe resource base to higher levels such as the on-line system orthe network.andP;  Through the use of host-provided data and solicitedheart-beat/probe-like information obtained by software processeson the Control Point machines called virtual people, real peopleare able to deal intelligently with complex resources.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     AutomationData ProcessingMISHuman Factors.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>